http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: To ensure that Nevada students are prepared for life in the digital age, students must be proficient technology users. It is no longer adequate for instruction to focus solely on basic technology skills as was the basis of previous versions of the Nevada Computer and Technology Standards. Rapid changes in our global society and technological advancements warrant changes to the ways technologies are integrated into classroom instruction. The standards contained in this document still address basic competence, and also incorporate the skills and knowledge that students require to learn effectively and live productively in an increasingly digital society.

Use digital tools to brainstorm and organize new ideas.
Process new ideas based on existing knowledge to brainstorm solutions to an authentic problem using digital tools.
Apply existing knowledge to independently generate new ideas, products, or processes with digital tools.

Create original works as a means of personal or group expression.

Create an original work using digital tools, including planning, research, editing, and production.
Use models and simulations to explore complex systems and issues.

Identify and represent trends and make predictions using classroom data.

Collaborate to create and publish digital products for authentic audiences in a variety of digital environments.

Communicate using digital text, images, sound, and video.

Develop cultural understanding and global awareness by engaging with learners of other cultures.
Use digital resources to learn about places, people, celebrations, and maps.
Use digital resources to research about places, people, and world cultures.
Use digital resources to communicate with peers and others from a variety of cultures and places.
Interact electronically with culturally diverse groups for specific purposes.
Contribute to project teams to produce original works or solve problems.
Work in a team to solve problems using digital tools.
Contribute to a group production of an original digital work.
Describe a variety of ways to interact and contribute to a digital product.
Contribute to project teams to produce original works or solve problems.
Choose a method of electronically interacting for a specific goal or purpose.
Contribute electronically to a group project that identifies a problem, presents solutions, and evaluates the solutions.

Use digital tools to plan a timeline and track progress for a research project.
Use digital tools to plan and organize research-based inquiry.
Use digital tools to plan a timeline, track progress, and cite sources for a research project.

Locate, organize, analyze, evaluate, synthesize, and ethically use information from a variety of sources and media.

Select and use a digital tool appropriate to a task.
Evaluate and compare facts and opinions in digital content sources and describe the point of view.
Select and justify using appropriate digital resources to accomplish a variety of tasks.

Plan and manage activities to develop a solution or complete a project.
Use a digital planning tool.
Plan and manage projects using a digital planning tool.

Analyze the capabilities and limitations of several different digital planning tools for developing solutions or for completing a project.
Collect and analyze data to identify solutions and/or make informed decisions.

Use multiple processes to explore alternative solutions and diverse perspectives on authentic problems and present a solution using digital tools.

Use multiple processes and consider diverse perspectives to derive original solutions to authentic problems using digital resources and assess their potential to address social, lifelong learning, and career needs.
